26:49.420 --> 27:01.600
trying to keep up with the area, which is getting harder and harder to do, So,
no, I actually do write it because I have a great fondness for it,

27:04.680 --> 27:17.040
and I am familiar in general with all of the outlines of the field. You think
it's being neglected or that it should have more of a place, say, in the

27:17.040 --> 27:27.180
classroom or the traditional literary mainstream, or is it something that
belongs in its own category? I don't know, this can be argued in a number of

27:27.180 --> 27:37.740
ways, of course. There are those who say there was no separate genre of science
fiction until 1926 when Gernsbach published the first science fiction magazine

27:37.740 --> 27:48.840
and had to call it something. The term eventually got coined. Before that, if H
.G. Wells had done a novel or Jules Verne, it would just be shelved in the

27:48.840 --> 27:53.800
library along with all the other works of general fiction It might just be
called a scientific romance.

27:56.420 --> 28:02.020
On the other hand, a

28:02.020 --> 28:13.320
lot of stuff is published these days. That is science fiction that is not called
science fiction, depending on who writes it, of course. Back when On the Beach

28:13.320 --> 28:21.420
was published, it wasn't published as science fiction. You can think of numerous
examples, and of course, in recent years, There have been science fiction novels

28:21.420 --> 28:26.460
which have made the bestseller list, but it

28:26.460 --> 28:30.040
is a special area for me.

28:43.180 --> 29:01.100
It is, for one reason, And one of the few special places where you still deal
with characters other than those which occur in the modern realistic or

29:01.100 --> 29:12.940
naturalistic novel. going back to the critic Northrop Frye who broke characters
into various modes, science fiction is one of the few places outside of say

29:12.940 --> 29:23.640
modern poetry where a writer can deal with characters in what he called the high
mimetic or the mythic modes that is characters who are greater than their fellow

29:23.640 --> 29:36.700
man or characters who are godlike sometimes in that science fiction does deal
with mutants and aliens and sentient computers and cyborgs and robots, what have

29:36.700 --> 29:45.260
you. Just all categories of beings which are different than the characters you
meet with in a naturalistic or realistic novel. So in that sense, and I think

29:45.260 --> 29:54.780
this is one of the great virtues of science fiction, it gives the writer more
scope for exploration in terms of character than just general fiction. So there

29:54.780 --> 30:10.400
is if this does get injected and taken up by mainstream, I would be very
surprised really. I think that science fiction periodically undergoes

30:13.940 --> 30:25.840
hits a peak. I think it's a cyclical thing that it is eventually taken up for a
while, considered, and then something new happens. I think it's more a matter of

30:25.840 --> 30:34.740
fashion and taste than it is something enduring and i think it

30:34.740 --> 30:42.360
is doubtless better known now than ever was before and it's history and it it
there will come a point i think when it's even better known but i i don't know

30:42.360 --> 30:53.720
that it will ever ultimately be merged with the mainstream of fiction of course
the mainstream of fiction 50 years from now may sound like science fiction today

30:53.720 --> 30:56.480
but that's a little bit different

